{"id": "pretrain-edu-001", "mode": "pretrain", "language": "en", "domain": "education", "difficulty": "introductory", "title": "The Basics of Photosynthesis", "text": "Plants convert sunlight into chemical energy through photosynthesis. Chlorophyll molecules within chloroplasts absorb photons, exciting electrons that drive a chain of reactions. Water molecules split, releasing oxygen as a byproduct, while carbon dioxide from the air gets fixed into glucose. This process sustains most life on Earth by producing both oxygen and organic compounds.", "metadata": {"source": "kimi_synthetic", "mode": "pretrain", "generated_at": "2026-04-25T19:05:28.306977+00:00", "prompt_version": "v2", "estimated_tokens": 95}}
{"id": "pretrain-jp-002", "mode": "pretrain", "language": "ja", "domain": "japanese", "difficulty": "intermediate", "title": "茶道の基本", "text": "茶道は、単なる飲み物を楽しむ行為ではなく、精神的な修養と人間関係の調和を重んじる日本の伝統文化である。点前の所作には、お辞儀の角度、茶碗の向き、茶筅の扱い方など、細かい決まりが存在する。亭主は季節や時間帯、客人の身分に応じて掛け軸や花入れの花を選び、茶室の空間全体で一期一会の精神を表現する。濃茶と薄茶の温度や濃さの違いを理解し、和敬清寂の心を持って接することが求められる。", "metadata": {"source": "kimi_synthetic", "mode": "pretrain", "generated_at": "2026-04-25T19:05:28.306977+00:00", "prompt_version": "v2", "estimated_tokens": 180}}
{"id": "pretrain-prog-003", "mode": "pretrain", "language": "en", "domain": "programming", "difficulty": "intermediate", "title": "Python Generators and Memory Efficiency", "text": "Generators in Python provide a memory-efficient alternative to lists when handling large datasets. Instead of computing all values upfront and storing them in memory, a generator yields items one at a time using lazy evaluation. The yield keyword suspends function execution, preserving local variables, and resumes on the next iteration. For example, reading a ten-gigabyte log file line by line with a generator uses constant memory, whereas loading it into a list would exhaust available RAM. Generator expressions, written with parentheses instead of square brackets, offer concise syntax for simple transformations.", "metadata": {"source": "kimi_synthetic", "mode": "pretrain", "generated_at": "2026-04-25T19:05:28.306977+00:00", "prompt_version": "v2", "estimated_tokens": 110}}
{"id": "pretrain-bil-004", "mode": "pretrain", "language": "mixed", "domain": "bilingual", "difficulty": "advanced", "title": "経済学における機会費用 / Opportunity Cost in Economics", "text": "機会費用（opportunity cost）とは、ある選択をした際に放棄した最良の代替案の価値を指す。When a government allocates funds to build a highway, the opportunity cost includes the hospital, school, or research facility that could have been constructed with the same budget. この概念は、資源が希少である限り、あらゆる経済的決定に内在している。Marginal analysis helps compare additional benefits against additional opportunity costs to reach optimal decisions. 個人の時間配分、企業の生産計画、国家の財政政策に至るまで、機会費用の考え方は一貫して適用される。", "metadata": {"source": "kimi_synthetic", "mode": "pretrain", "generated_at": "2026-04-25T19:05:28.306977+00:00", "prompt_version": "v2", "estimated_tokens": 170}}
{"id": "pretrain-sci-005", "mode": "pretrain", "language": "en", "domain": "science", "difficulty": "advanced", "title": "Wave-Particle Duality in Quantum Systems", "text": "The double-slit experiment reveals that individual photons or electrons build up an interference pattern over time, suggesting each particle traverses both paths simultaneously until measurement collapses the wavefunction. This superposition principle defies classical intuition but has been verified across scales from subatomic particles to complex molecules like buckyballs. The de Broglie wavelength lambda equals Planck's constant divided by momentum, predicting that heavier particles require correspondingly tighter experimental geometries to observe diffraction effects. Decoherence theory explains how environmental interactions rapidly suppress quantum behavior in macroscopic objects without invoking conscious observers.", "metadata": {"source": "kimi_synthetic", "mode": "pretrain", "generated_at": "2026-04-25T19:05:28.306977+00:00", "prompt_version": "v2", "estimated_tokens": 125}}
{"id": "pretrain-hist-006", "mode": "pretrain", "language": "en", "domain": "history", "difficulty": "introductory", "title": "Roman Engineering and Infrastructure", "text": "The Roman Empire constructed approximately four hundred thousand kilometers of roads, enabling rapid military movement and trade across three continents. Roman engineers perfected the arch and concrete formula using volcanic ash, creating structures like the Pantheon with its unreinforced concrete dome spanning forty-three meters. Aqueducts transported water using gravity alone, with gradients as shallow as thirty-four centimeters per kilometer. These innovations required standardized measurement, organized labor, and meticulous surveying techniques that remained unsurpassed for over a millennium.", "metadata": {"source": "kimi_synthetic", "mode": "pretrain", "generated_at": "2026-04-25T19:05:28.306977+00:00", "prompt_version": "v2", "estimated_tokens": 105}}
{"id": "pretrain-eve-007", "mode": "pretrain", "language": "en", "domain": "everyday", "difficulty": "introductory", "title": "Sourdough Bread Fundamentals", "text": "Sourdough leavening relies on wild yeast and lactic acid bacteria rather than commercial yeast strains. A starter culture requires regular feeding with equal parts flour and water to maintain acidity and vigor. Fermentation time depends on ambient temperature; cooler environments slow microbial activity and develop tangier flavors. The autolyse stage, mixing flour and water before adding salt, hydrates gluten proteins and reduces kneading requirements. Scoring the loaf surface with a lame controls expansion direction during oven spring, producing the characteristic ear and open crumb structure prized by bakers.", "metadata": {"source": "kimi_synthetic", "mode": "pretrain", "generated_at": "2026-04-25T19:05:28.306977+00:00", "prompt_version": "v2", "estimated_tokens": 110}}
{"id": "pretrain-sd-008", "mode": "pretrain", "language": "en", "domain": "structured-data", "difficulty": "intermediate", "title": "Database Normalization Principles", "text": "First normal form requires atomic values in every column and eliminates repeating groups. Second normal form removes partial dependencies, ensuring non-key attributes depend on the entire primary key rather than a subset. Third normal form eliminates transitive dependencies where non-key attributes depend on other non-key attributes. Boyce-Codd normal form strengthens these requirements so that every determinant qualifies as a candidate key. While normalization reduces data redundancy and prevents update anomalies, excessive normalization can degrade query performance through excessive joins. Denormalization strategically reintroduces redundancy in read-heavy analytical workloads to improve retrieval speed.", "metadata": {"source": "kimi_synthetic", "mode": "pretrain", "generated_at": "2026-04-25T19:05:28.306977+00:00", "prompt_version": "v2", "estimated_tokens": 115}}
{"id": "pretrain-fic-009", "mode": "pretrain", "language": "en", "domain": "original-fiction", "difficulty": "intermediate", "title": "The Cartographer's Last Map", "text": "Elara found the parchment in a sealed brass tube beneath the observatory floorboards. The ink shifted when viewed from different angles, displaying coastlines that corresponded to no known geography. She measured angles against star charts from 1847 and discovered the shorelines matched a continent that spectroscopic surveys had detected orbiting Proxima Centauri the previous month. The paper fiber dated to 1923. In the margin, her grandmother's handwriting noted: 'First draft. Scale is time, not distance.'", "metadata": {"source": "kimi_synthetic", "mode": "pretrain", "generated_at": "2026-04-25T19:05:28.306977+00:00", "prompt_version": "v2", "estimated_tokens": 110}}
{"id": "pretrain-math-010", "mode": "pretrain", "language": "en", "domain": "math", "difficulty": "intermediate", "title": "Completing the Square: A Worked Example", "text": "Consider the quadratic equation x squared minus six x plus five equals zero. To complete the square, take half of the linear coefficient negative six, yielding negative three, then square it to obtain nine. Rewrite the expression as x squared minus six x plus nine minus nine plus five, which groups into x minus three squared minus four. Setting this equal to zero gives x minus three squared equals four. Taking square roots produces x minus three equals plus or minus two, so the solutions are x equals five and x equals one. This method generalizes to any quadratic and reveals the vertex form directly.", "metadata": {"source": "kimi_synthetic", "mode": "pretrain", "generated_at": "2026-04-25T19:05:28.306977+00:00", "prompt_version": "v2", "estimated_tokens": 130}}
{"id": "pretrain-ps-011", "mode": "pretrain", "language": "en", "domain": "problem-solution", "difficulty": "advanced", "title": "Resolving Consensus Failures in Distributed Systems", "text": "When a Raft cluster experiences network partitioning, the leader may continue accepting writes in a minority partition while a new leader emerges in the majority partition. After healing, conflicting log entries require careful reconciliation. The solution involves term numbers: each server rejects AppendEntries RPCs with stale terms, and leaders step down upon discovering higher terms. During recovery, the new leader overwrites uncommitted entries from the deposed leader because its log is guaranteed to contain all entries committed in previous terms. Implementations should include pre-vote stages to prevent disrupted followers from triggering unnecessary elections when rejoining.", "metadata": {"source": "kimi_synthetic", "mode": "pretrain", "generated_at": "2026-04-25T19:05:28.306977+00:00", "prompt_version": "v2", "estimated_tokens": 125}}
{"id": "pretrain-ce-012", "mode": "pretrain", "language": "en", "domain": "code-explanation", "difficulty": "introductory", "title": "How Bubble Sort Works", "text": "Bubble sort repeatedly steps through a list, comparing adjacent elements and swapping them if they are in the wrong order. Each complete pass through the list guarantees that the largest unsorted element reaches its final position, similar to a bubble rising to the surface. For an array of n elements, the algorithm requires at most n minus one passes. An optimization tracks whether any swaps occurred during a pass; if none occurred, the list is already sorted and the algorithm can terminate early. While simple to implement, bubble sort has quadratic time complexity in the average and worst cases, making it unsuitable for large datasets.", "metadata": {"source": "kimi_synthetic", "mode": "pretrain", "generated_at": "2026-04-25T19:05:28.306977+00:00", "prompt_version": "v2", "estimated_tokens": 120}}
